# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atophan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atophan/atophan] Cinchophen was first introduced in 1908 as 'Atophan' and used for the treatment of gout and arthritis.
[src:atophan/atophan] It was efficacious at reducing the buildup of uric acid and became a popular medicine.
[src:atophan/atophan] Further studies in 1911 and 1912 were successful in isolating metabolites of cinchophen from human urine.
[src:atophan/atophan] During the 1920s, cases of severe adverse effects such as liver damage and cirrhosis had been clinically observed; the first case of jaundice was recorded in 1923 and the first fatality occurred in 1925.
[src:atophan/atophan] Cinchophen was considered to be too dangerous for human use in most countries but has applications in veterinary medicine as a treatment for osteoarthritis in dogs.
[src:atophan/atophan] Cinchophen can be administered orally in tablet form or intravenously in liquid form.
[src:atophan/atophan] Cinchophen toxicity may present 6 to 12 hours after administration.
[src:atophan/atophan] Symptoms can include hyperventilation, hyperthermia (fever), gastrointestinal discomfort, diarrhoea, hives, vomiting, delirium, hepatitis, jaundice, anorexia, convulsions, coma and death.
[src:atophan/atophan] Fatty degeneration of the heart and kidneys, necrosis of hepatic cells in addition to yellow atrophy of the liver have been recorded in autopsy findings.
[src:atophan/atophan] Cinchophen administration should be immediately ceased if symptoms occur.
[src:atophan/atophan] There is no cure for acute cinchophen poisoning but early diagnosis and symptomatic treatments may be effective.
[src:atophan/atophan] Calcium lactate may be used to treat hives and oral or intravenous glucose can relieve gastrointestinal symptoms.
[src:atophan/atophan] If glucose is given, insulin may be needed to protect the liver from further damage.
[src:atophan/atophan] Oral alkali treatments can combat acidosis and anti-emetics may be required to manage nausea and vomiting.
[src:atophan/atophan] Cinchophen is the main active ingredient in prednoleucotropin (PLT), a medication used in the treatment of osteoarthritis in dogs.
[src:atophan/atophan] PLT may produce analgesic and anti-pyretic effects at higher doses.
[src:atophan/atophan] Osteoarthritic dogs treated with PLT have shown significant improvement of joint mobility, stiffness, lameness and weight bearing capacity.
[src:atophan/atophan] When administered correctly, PLT has shown similar clinical efficacy to phenylbutazone.
[src:atophan/atophan] The effects of PLT toxicity in dogs are similar to cinchophen toxicity in humans and include hepatotoxicity and gastric ulceration.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] INNs are intended to make communication more precise by providing a unique standard name for each active ingredient, to avoid prescribing errors.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] The INN system was initiated by the World Health Organization (WHO) in 1953.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] Having unambiguous standard names for each pharmaceutical substance (standardization of drug nomenclature) is important because a drug may be sold under many different brand names, or a branded medication may contain more than one drug.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] For example, the branded medications Celexa, Celapram and Citrol all contain the same active ingredient whose INN is citalopram.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] The antibacterial medication known as co-trimoxazole as well as those under the brand names Bactrim and Septran all contain two active ingredients easily recognisable by their INN: trimethoprim and sulfamethoxazole.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] An established INN is known as a *recommended* INN (rINN), while a name that is still being considered is called a *proposed* INN (pINN).
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] National nonproprietary names such as British Approved Names (BAN), Dénominations Communes Françaises (DCF), Japanese Adopted Names (JAN) and United States Adopted Names (USAN) are nowadays, with rare exceptions, identical to the INN.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] Each drug's INN is unique but may contain a **stem** that is shared with other drugs of the same class.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] In this context, a stem is a syllable (or syllables) created to evoke in the name the pharmacological mechanism of action or the chemical structure of the substance.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] Stems are mostly placed word-finally (suffixes), but in some cases word-initial stems (prefixes) are used.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] For example, the beta blocker drugs propranolol and atenolol share the stem *-olol* (as a suffix), and the benzodiazepine drugs lorazepam and diazepam share the stem *-azepam* (also a suffix) The list of stems in use are collected in a publication informally known as the *Stem Book*.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] The term *stem* is not used consistently in linguistics.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] It has been defined as a form to which affixes (of any type) can be attached.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] Under a different and apparently more common view, this is the definition of a root, while a stem consists of the root plus optional derivational affixes, meaning that it is the part of a word to which inflectional affixes are added.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] INN stems employ the first definition, while under the more common alternative they would be described as roots.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] Pharmacology and pharmacotherapy (like health care generally) are universally relevant around the world, making translingual communication about them an important goal.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] An interlingual perspective is thus useful in drug nomenclature.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] The WHO issues INNs in English, Latin, French, Russian, Spanish, Arabic, and Chinese.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] A drug's INNs are often cognates across most or all of the languages, but they also allow small inflectional, diacritic, and transliterational differences that are usually transparent and trivial for nonspeakers (as is true of most international scientific vocabulary).
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] For example, although *ibuprofenum* (la) has an inflectional difference from *ibuprofen* (en), and although *ibuprofène* (fr) has a diacritic difference, the differences are trivial; users can easily recognize the "same word".
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] Although *Ибупрофе́н* (ru) and *ibuprofen* (en) have a transliteration difference, they sound similar, and for Russian speakers who can recognize Latin script or English speakers who can recognize Cyrillic script, they look similar; users can recognize the "same word".
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] Thus, INNs make medicines bought anywhere in the world as easily identifiable as possible to people who do not speak that language.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] Notably, the "same word" principle allows health professionals and patients who do not speak the same language to communicate to some degree and to avoid potentially life-threatening confusions from drug interactions.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] To facilitate the translation and pronunciation of INN, "f" should be used instead of "ph", "t" instead of "th", "e" instead of "ae" or "oe", and "i" instead of "y"; the use of the letters "h" and "k" should be avoided.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] Many drugs are supplied as salts, with a cation and an anion.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] The way the INN system handles these is explained by the WHO at its "Guidance on INN" webpage.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] For example, amfetamine and oxacillin are INNs, whereas various salts of these compounds – e.g., *amfetamine sulfate* and *oxacillin sodium* – are **modified INNs** (**INNM**).
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] Several countries had created their own nonproprietary naming system before the INN was created, and in many cases, the names created under the old systems continue to be used in those countries.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] Other naming systems not listed above include France's Dénomination Commune Française (DCF) and Italy's Denominazione Comune Italiana (DCIT).
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] The School of INN is a WHO International Nonproprietary Name Programme initiative launched in 2019, which aims to provide information to pharmacy, medical and health students, as well as health professionals and other stakeholders on how an INN is designed and constructed.
[src:atophan/international-nonproprietary-name] Users can take self-administered courses using its free online learning platform.
